```xml
<manifest xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    package="com.madhub.socialmediascheduler">

    <!-- 
        The manifest file declares essential information about the application, including 
        components and permissions required for a social media scheduling tool. 
        This application automates content management across multiple platforms. 
    -->

    <application
        android:allowBackup="true"
        android:icon="@mipmap/ic_launcher"
        android:label="@string/app_name"
        android:theme="@style/AppTheme">
        
        <!-- 
            The MainActivity serves as the entry point of the application.
            In this scenario, when the user opens the app, this activity initializes 
            the user interface and allows them to configure their social media accounts 
            for scheduling posts.
        -->
        <activity
            android:name=".MainActivity"
            android:exported="true">
            <intent-filter>
                <action android:name="android.intent.action.MAIN" />
                <category android:name="android.intent.category.LAUNCHER" />
            </intent-filter>
        </activity>

        <!-- 
            The AutomationService is a background service that automates the posting 
            of scheduled content to various social media platforms. 
            Workflow step: This service runs in the background to ensure that posts 
            are published at the configured times without requiring user intervention.
        -->
        <service
            android:name=".AutomationService"
            android:enabled="true"
            android:exported="false">
        </service>
    </application>

    <!-- 
        Permissions are declared here to enable specific functionalities of the app. 
        In this scenario, these permissions ensure that the application can access the 
        internet for posting content on social media platforms and can read/write content 
        to storage for managing media files.
    -->

    <!-- 
        The INTERNET permission allows the application to connect to the internet to 
        send scheduled posts to various social media platforms such as Facebook, Instagram, 
        and TikTok.
    -->
    <uses-permission android:name="android.permission.INTERNET"/>

    <!-- 
        The WRITE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE permission allows the application to save media files 
        required for posts. Users may upload images or videos, which need to be stored 
        on the device. 
    -->
    <uses-permission android:name="android.permission.WRITE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE"/>
    
    <!-- 
        The READ_EXTERNAL_STORAGE permission enables the app to read media files 
        stored on the device. This is crucial for selecting images or videos for 
        scheduling posts.
    -->
    <uses-permission android:name="android.permission.READ_EXTERNAL_STORAGE"/>

    <!-- 
        The ACCESS_NETWORK_STATE permission checks if the device is connected to the internet. 
        This is useful to ensure that scheduled posts can be uploaded successfully 
        at the right times.
    -->
    <uses-permission android:name="android.permission.ACCESS_NETWORK_STATE"/>

    <!-- 
        By declaring these permissions, we ensure that the application can 
        effectively manage social media content, providing a seamless user experience 
        while adhering to platform compliance standards.
    -->

</manifest>
```

### Explanation of the AndroidManifest.xml Configuration

- **MainActivity**: Serves as the entry point of the application, allowing users to interactively set up their social media accounts and schedule posts.
- **AutomationService**: Runs in the background to reliably automate the publication of scheduled posts, ensuring that users can manage their social media presence effectively even when they are not actively using the app.
- **Permissions**: The selected permissions are crucial for the app's functionality. They enable internet connectivity for posting, and access to external storage for media management, which is essential for a social media scheduling tool.

